            <p class="caption">Tsuivan is a popular and affordable food in Mongolia. It is a great alternative to rice.
            </p>


            <h2>Khorkhog</h2>
            <p>Khorkhog, often referred to as Mongolian barbecue, is a festive and special occasion dish that embodies
                the hearty, communal spirit of Mongolia. Traditionally prepared during the summer and celebrations like
                Naadam, this dish involves cooking meat—usually mutton or goat—inside a sealed metal container with hot
                stones. These stones, heated over an open fire, not only cook the meat but infuse it with a smoky,
                earthy flavor that makes Khorkhog truly unique. Vegetables like potatoes and carrots are often added,
                absorbing the savory juices for a rich and satisfying meal.
                A cherished part of the experience is handling the hot stones once the dish is ready. These stones,
                believed to have therapeutic properties, are passed around, warming hands and sparking conversations.
                Khorkhog is more than just food; it’s a tradition that brings people together, creating unforgettable
                memories around a shared, flavorful feast.</p>
            <img src="/images/mongolia/food.jpg" alt="Khorkhog"
                style="display: block; margin: 0 auto; width: 60%; border-radius: 8px;">
            <p class="caption">Khorkhog is a unique dish enjoyed during gatherings and special occasions.</p>
