            <h2>Weather</h2>
            <p> Mongolia experiences a **continental climate**, characterized by extreme variations in temperature and
                weather conditions. Known as the "Land of Blue Sky," Mongolia enjoys over 250 sunny days a year. Winters
                are long and harsh, with temperatures often dropping below -30°C (-22°F), especially in January, the
                coldest month. Summers, by contrast, are warm and short, with temperatures ranging from 20°C to 30°C
                (68°F to 86°F), particularly in July.
                Rainfall is scarce, with most precipitation occurring between June and August, making the country
                largely arid or semi-arid. The Gobi Desert in the south experiences dry, windy conditions, while the
                northern and central regions have a more temperate climate. The significant temperature swings between
                day and night and across seasons are a hallmark of Mongolia's weather, reflecting its vast, open steppes
                and high-altitude geography. </p>
